llation#common-pitfalls","content":"**Fix:** whest supports NumPy `>=2.0.0,<2.3.0` (default install uses NumPy 2.2). Using `uv` handles this automatically. If you installed manually, check your NumPy version:"},"456":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/installation-14","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/installation","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/installation#related-pages","content":"Quickstart — run your first FLOP-counted computation"},"457":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","type":"page","content":"Quickstart","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Getting Started"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart"},"458":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-0","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"459":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-1","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#quickest-possible-start","content":"Quickest possible start"},"460":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-2","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"What you'll see"},"461":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-3","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#next-steps","content":"Next steps"},"462":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-4","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","content":"*Run your first FLOP-counted computation in under 2 minutes.*"},"463":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-5","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","content":"**You will learn:**"},"464":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-6","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","content":"How to run a FLOP-counted computation with the global default budget"},"465":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-7","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","content":"How to read the budget summary output"},"466":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-8","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#prerequisites","content":"Installation"},"467":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-9","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#quickest-possible-start","content":"You do not need to set up a budget context to start counting FLOPs. whest activates a global default context the first time any counted operation runs. The default budget is 1e15 FLOPs (configurable via the `WHEST_DEFAULT_BUDGET` environment variable)."},"468":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-10","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#quickest-possible-start","content":"Save this as `first_budget.py`:"},"469":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-11","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#quickest-possible-start","content":"Run it:"},"470":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-12","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"**Reading the output:**"},"471":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-13","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"**Top rows:** `Used` is the total FLOP count spent so far across the current session, and `Remaining` shows the implicit global headroom"},"472":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-14","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"**Flat default:** the summary stays flat unless you explicitly ask for `we.budget_summary(by_namespace=True)`"},"473":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-15","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"**Operations table:** the 10-layer MLP spreads FLOPs roughly equally across `random.randn`, `multiply`, `array`, and `einsum` (\\~25% each); activations (`maximum`) are comparatively cheap, and the Kaiming scale `sqrt` adds just 1 FLOP"},"474":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-16","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#what-youll-see","content":"If you want namespace attribution, opt in separately:"},"475":{"id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart-17","page_id":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/getting-started/quickstart#next-steps","content":"Ready for budget limits? See the Competition Guide."},"476":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"page","content":"Budget Planning & Debugging","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning"},"477":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#estimate-before-running","content":"Estimate before running"},"478":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#budget-breakdown-example","content":"Budget breakdown example"},"479":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#read-the-budget-summary","content":"Read the budget summary"},"480":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"Add a time limit when FLOPs are not the only risk"},"481":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Diagnose overruns"},"482":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"What to do next"},"483":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"*Estimate costs before running and diagnose overruns after.*"},"484":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"**You will learn:**"},"485":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"How to use cost query functions to estimate FLOPs without executing"},"486":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"How to read and interpret the budget summary"},"487":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"How to diagnose expensive operations using the operation log"},"488":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","content":"Optimization strategies for reducing FLOP consumption"},"489":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#estimate-before-running","content":"whest provides cost query functions that compute FLOP costs from shapes without executing anything or touching the budget. Use these to plan before committing FLOPs:"},"490":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#estimate-before-running","content":"For multi-operand einsums (3+ operands), use `we.einsum_path()` to see the step-by-step contraction breakdown with per-step costs and symmetry savings:"},"491":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#estimate-before-running","content":"`we.einsum_path()` does not execute the contraction, but it does record a nominal 1-FLOP planning event so the path query itself is still visible in the operation log."},"492":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#budget-breakdown-example","content":"Plan a multi-step computation before executing:"},"493":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#read-the-budget-summary","content":"Call `we.budget_summary()` after your computation for a human-readable breakdown, or `budget.summary()` inside a context. Pass `by_namespace=True` when you want dotted namespace attribution:"},"494":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#read-the-budget-summary","content":"The summary shows cost per operation type, sorted by highest cost first. Look for operations consuming a disproportionate share of the budget. When you opt into `by_namespace=True`, the display adds a namespace breakdown for the exact dotted paths recorded in that run."},"495":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#read-the-budget-summary","content":"For programmatic analysis, use `we.budget_summary_dict()`:"},"496":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#read-the-budget-summary","content":"Use `we.budget_summary_dict(by_namespace=True)` for exact per-namespace breakdowns keyed by the full dotted path:"},"497":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"Some operations are analytically cheap enough to fit the FLOP budget but still\nslow in practice. Use `wall_time_limit_s` on the same `BudgetContext` when you\nwant a cooperative wall-clock deadline in addition to the FLOP cap:"},"498":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"When the time limit is exceeded, whest raises `TimeExhaustedError` at the next\noperation boundary. The summary exposes three timing views:"},"499":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"`wall_time_s`: total elapsed time for the context"},"500":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"`tracked_time_s`: time spent inside counted NumPy calls"},"501":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"`untracked_time_s`: everything else in the context (`wall_time_s - tracked_time_s`)"},"502":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#add-a-time-limit-when-flops-are-not-the-only-risk","content":"Use `budget.summary()` when you want the current context's timings, and\n`we.budget_summary()` when you want the accumulated session/global view."},"503":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"When you hit a `BudgetExhaustedError`, the budget's operation log gives per-call detail:"},"504":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Each `OpRecord` contains:"},"505":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Field"},"506":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Description"},"507":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`op_name`"},"508":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Operation name (e.g., `\"einsum\"`, `\"exp\"`)"},"509":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`namespace`"},"510":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Effective namespace path recorded for that operation"},"511":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`subscripts`"},"512":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Einsum subscript string, or `None`"},"513":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`shapes`"},"514":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Tuple of input shapes"},"515":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`flop_cost`"},"516":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"FLOP cost of this single call"},"517":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"`cumulative`"},"518":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Running total after this call"},"519":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"Look for the operation where `cumulative` jumps sharply -- that is your most expensive call."},"520":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#diagnose-overruns","content":"For real-time monitoring during long computations, use the live budget display:"},"521":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"Once you have identified the expensive operations, apply these strategies:"},"522":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"**Reduce dimensions.** If `random.randn(1024, 1024)` is too expensive, try smaller arrays. A 512x512 matrix costs 1/4 the FLOPs of a 1024x1024 matrix for a matmul."},"523":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"**Exploit symmetry.** If operands are symmetric, use `we.as_symmetric()` to halve pointwise costs and significantly reduce einsum costs. See Symmetry Savings."},"524":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"**Use cheaper operations.** A matrix-vector product costs `m*n` FLOPs, while a matrix-matrix product costs `m*n*k`. Avoid computing full matrix products when you only need a few rows or a single vector result."},"525":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"**Increase budget.** If the computation is genuinely needed and you have headroom, raise `flop_budget` on the `BudgetContext`."},"526":{"id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning-49","page_id":"/docs/guides/budget-planning","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/budget-planning#what-to-do-next","content":"**Split into phases.** Use namespaces to attribute different phases without splitting the FLOP budget into child budgets:"},"527":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"page","content":"Einsum Patterns","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum"},"528":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"529":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#common-patterns","content":"Common patterns"},"530":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"Cost formula"},"531":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#wedot-and-wematmul","content":"we.dot and we.matmul"},"532":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#symmetric-tensors","content":"Symmetric tensors"},"533":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#inspecting-costs","content":"Inspecting costs"},"534":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#custom-contraction-paths","content":"Custom contraction paths"},"535":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-7","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#path-caching","content":"Path caching"},"536":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-8","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cache-management","content":"Cache management"},"537":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-9","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#common-pitfalls","content":"Common pitfalls"},"538":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-10","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/einsum#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"539":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-11","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"*Use this page to understand `we.einsum` -- the core computation primitive in whest.*"},"540":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-12","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"**You will learn:**"},"541":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-13","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"How to write common einsum patterns and understand their FLOP costs"},"542":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-14","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"How to use symmetric tensors with einsum for cost savings"},"543":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-15","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"How to inspect and customize contraction paths"},"544":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-16","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum","content":"How to leverage path caching for repeated operations"},"545":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-17","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#prerequisites","content":"Quickstart"},"546":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-18","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"The cost of an einsum is the sum of per-step costs along the optimal contraction path. Every einsum — even a simple two-operand one — goes through the opt\\_einsum path optimizer (a symmetry-aware fork of opt\\_einsum)."},"547":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-19","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"For each pairwise step:"},"548":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-20","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"Each FMA (fused multiply-add) counts as 1 operation, so the cost is\nsimply the product of all index dimensions with no factor-of-2."},"549":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-21","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"For `'ij,jk->ik'` with shapes `(256, 256)` and `(256, 256)`:"},"550":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-22","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"Indices: i=256, j=256, k=256"},"551":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-23","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"Cost: 256 x 256 x 256 = 16,777,216"},"552":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-24","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"For multi-operand einsums (3+ tensors), whest automatically decomposes the contraction into optimal pairwise steps. The total cost is the sum of per-step costs."},"553":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-25","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#cost-formula","content":"When symmetric tensors are involved, each step's cost is further reduced by the ratio of unique output elements to total output elements. See Symmetry Savings for the full practical guide."},"554":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-26","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#wedot-and-wematmul","content":"`we.dot(A, B)` and `we.matmul(A, B)` are equivalent to the corresponding einsum and have the same FLOP cost."},"555":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-27","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#symmetric-tensors","content":"There are two separate symmetry declarations — one for inputs, one for outputs:"},"556":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-28","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#symmetric-tensors","content":"**Input symmetry** — wrap with `we.as_symmetric()` before passing to einsum. The optimizer automatically uses symmetry to choose the best contraction order and charges reduced costs:"},"557":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-29","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#symmetric-tensors","content":"**Output symmetry** — pass `symmetric_axes` to `einsum()` to declare that the result is symmetric. This wraps the output as a `SymmetricTensor` so downstream operations benefit from reduced costs. It does NOT affect the cost of this einsum — it's a declaration about the result's structure:"},"558":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-30","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#symmetric-tensors","content":"For the full symmetry guide, see Symmetry Savings."},"559":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-31","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#inspecting-costs","content":"`we.einsum_path()` previews the contraction plan without executing the contraction itself. Planning is cheap: it records a nominal 1-FLOP `einsum_path` event, but none of the contraction FLOPs are spent."},"560":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-32","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#inspecting-costs","content":"The printed table gives you the contraction order, naive-vs-optimized FLOP counts, largest intermediate, grouped index sizes, and one row per pairwise contraction step. Each step shows the chosen contract tuple, dense baseline, savings, BLAS tag, and any symmetry that survived into the intermediate."},"561":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-33","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#inspecting-costs","content":"For per-step debugging, call `print(info.format_table(verbose=True))`. The verbose view adds indented rows with the merged operand subset, the intermediate output shape, and the running cumulative cost."},"562":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-34","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#inspecting-costs","content":"`we.flops.einsum_cost()` returns the same cost that `einsum()` would deduct — one source of truth:"},"563":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-35","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#custom-contraction-paths","content":"By default whest finds the optimal contraction order automatically. You can override this by passing an explicit path — a list of int-tuples specifying which operand positions to contract at each step:"},"564":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-36","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#custom-contraction-paths","content":"You can also specify a completely custom path. Each tuple names the positions (in the current operand list) to contract; the result is appended to the end:"},"565":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-37","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#custom-contraction-paths","content":"Different paths may have different FLOP costs. Use `we.einsum_path()` to compare — it returns the plan without executing the contraction."},"566":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#path-caching","content":"Contraction paths are cached automatically in a module-level LRU cache.\nWhen you call `we.einsum()` with the same subscripts, shapes, optimizer,\nand symmetry structure, the path is reused from cache instead of being\nrecomputed. This makes repeated einsums in loops essentially free in\npath-finding overhead:"},"567":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#path-caching","content":"`we.einsum_path()` shares the same cache, so planning a path warms the\ncache for subsequent `we.einsum()` calls and vice versa."},"568":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#common-pitfalls","content":"**Symptom:** Unexpectedly high FLOP cost"},"569":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#common-pitfalls","content":"**Fix:** Check all index dimensions. A subscript like `'ijkl,jklm->im'` multiplies all five dimension sizes together. Use `we.flops.einsum_cost()` or `we.einsum_path()` to preview costs before executing."},"570":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#related-pages","content":"Symmetry Savings — full guide to symmetry mechanisms"},"571":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#related-pages","content":"API Reference — algorithms, symmetry support, and operation details"},"572":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#related-pages","content":"Plan Your Budget — query costs before executing"},"573":{"id":"/docs/guides/einsum-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/einsum","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/einsum#related-pages","content":"FLOP Counting Model — how costs are computed"},"574":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","type":"page","content":"FFT Operations","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/fft"},"575":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/fft#prerequisites","content":"Prerequis