lued transforms (`rfft`, `irfft`, `rfftn`, `irfftn`) cost roughly half of their complex counterparts because they exploit conjugate symmetry."},"613":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-38","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#real-vs-complex-transforms","content":"When your input is real-valued (which is common in signal processing), prefer `rfft` over `fft` — it costs half as much:"},"614":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-39","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#real-vs-complex-transforms","content":"The output of `rfft` has shape `(n//2 + 1,)` instead of `(n,)`, since the negative frequencies are redundant for real inputs."},"615":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-40","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#multi-dimensional-fft","content":"Use `fft2` for 2-D transforms (e.g., images) and `fftn` for arbitrary dimensions:"},"616":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-41","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#windowed-fft-pattern","content":"A common signal processing pattern — window the signal before FFT to reduce spectral leakage:"},"617":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-42","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#common-pitfalls","content":"**Symptom:** Using `we.fft.fft` on real data when `we.fft.rfft` would suffice"},"618":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-43","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#common-pitfalls","content":"**Fix:** `rfft` costs half as much. If your input is real-valued, always prefer `rfft`/`irfft` over `fft`/`ifft`."},"619":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-44","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#common-pitfalls","content":"**Symptom:** Unexpectedly high cost for multi-dimensional FFT"},"620":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-45","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#common-pitfalls","content":"**Fix:** The cost scales as $5 \\cdot \\prod n_\\{i\\} \\cdot \\lceil\\log_2(\\prod n_\\{i\\})\\rceil$. A 256x256 2-D FFT processes 65,536 elements, not 256. Use `fft_cost` to estimate before running."},"621":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-46","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#related-pages","content":"API Reference — full function signatures and docstrings"},"622":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-47","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#related-pages","content":"Plan Your Budget — general cost estimation workflow"},"623":{"id":"/docs/guides/fft-48","page_id":"/docs/guides/fft","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/guides/fft#related-pages","content":"FLOP Counting Model — how all costs are computed"},"624":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"page","content":"Linear Algebra","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Guides"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg"},"625":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-0","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#prerequisites","content":"Prerequisites"},"626":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-1","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#available-operations","content":"Available operations"},"627":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-2","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#decompositions","content":"Decompositions"},"628":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-3","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#solvers","content":"Solvers"},"629":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-4","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#properties","content":"Properties"},"630":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-5","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/guides/linalg#compound","content":"Compound"},"631":{"id":"/docs/guides/linalg-6","page_id":"/docs/guides/linalg","type":"heading"