-22","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How whest computes FLOP costs analytically from tensor shapes"},"1031":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-23","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How cost formulas work for each operation category (einsum, linalg, FFT, etc.)"},"1032":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-24","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How symmetry savings and per-operation weights modify costs"},"1033":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-25","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","content":"How the FLOP multiplier and namespaces interact with the cost model"},"1034":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-26","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#convention-fma--1-operation","content":"This codebase counts a fused multiply-add (a \\* b + c) as a **single operation**.\nHardware FMA units execute this in one instruction; the common textbook\nconvention of counting it as 2 (one multiply + one add) is **not** used here.\nAll cost formulae reflect this: a matrix multiply of dimensions\n(m, k) x (k, n) costs m*k*n operations, not 2*m*k\\*n."},"1035":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-27","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#why-flops-instead-of-wall-clock-time","content":"**Deterministic:** The same code always produces the same FLOP count, regardless of hardware"},"1036":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-28","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#why-flops-instead-of-wall-clock-time","content":"**Hardware-independent:** A matmul costs the same FLOPs on a laptop and a server"},"1037":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-29","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#why-flops-instead-of-wall-clock-time","content":"**Reproducible:** No variance from CPU scheduling, cache effects, or thermal throttling"},"1038":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-30","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#why-flops-instead-of-wall-clock-time","content":"**Composable:** You can sum individual operation costs to predict total cost"},"1039":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-31","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-costs-are-computed","content":"whest computes FLOP costs **analytically from tensor shapes**, not by measuring execution time."},"1040":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-32","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-costs-are-computed","content":"You call a counted operation (e.g., `we.einsum('ij,j->i', W, x)`)"},"1041":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-33","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-costs-are-computed","content":"whest computes the cost from the shapes: 256 × 256 = 65,536 FLOPs"},"1042":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-34","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-costs-are-computed","content":"The cost is checked against the remaining budget"},"1043":{"