el-108","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Pointwise** (unary/binary)"},"1117":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-109","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"unique\\_elements"},"1118":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-110","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$"},"1119":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-111","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Reduction**"},"1120":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-112","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"unique\\_elements"},"1121":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-113","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{input\\})$"},"1122":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-114","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Einsum** (symmetric contraction)"},"1123":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-115","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"Symmetry-reduced (see below)"},"1124":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-116","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"Full product"},"1125":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-117","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Solve**"},"1126":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-118","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3$"},"1127":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-119","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3$"},"1128":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-120","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Det / Slogdet**"},"1129":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-121","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3$"},"1130":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-122","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3$"},"1131":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-123","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"**Inv**"},"1132":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-124","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3/3 + n^3$"},"1133":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-125","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"$n^3$"},"1134":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-126","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetry-savings","content":"See Exploit Symmetry Savings for usage details."},"1135":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-127","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#subgraph-symmetry-detection","content":"Symmetry that reduces einsum costs comes from two complementary sources,\nboth unified under the **subgraph symmetry detection** algorithm:"},"1136":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-128","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#subgraph-symmetry-detection","content":"**Declared per-operand symmetry.** When an operand is wrapped with\n`we.as_symmetric()`, its symmetry groups are embedded in the bipartite\ngraph as U-vertex equivalence classes. These propagate into intermediate\ntensors automatically."},"1137":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-129","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#subgraph-symmetry-detection","content":"**Induced symmetry from repeated operands.** When the same Python object\nis passed at multiple operand positions, the subgraph oracle detects this\nvia Python identity (`is`) and derives symmetry groups on the output that\ncannot be seen from per-operand metadata alone."},"1138":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-130","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#subgraph-symmetry-detection","content":"The oracle builds a bipartite graph once per `contract_path` call and\nevaluates symmetry lazily per subset of operands encountered during path\nsearch. Both sources are merged via the same group-merging machinery, so a\ntensor that is both `SymmetricTensor` and also repeated in the subscript\nbenefits from both contributions simultaneously."},"1139":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-131","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#subgraph-symmetry-detection","content":"See the\nsymmetry guide\nfor usage examples, and the\nsubgraph symmetry explanation\nfor the algorithm walkthrough."},"1140":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-132","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#einsum-cost-model","content":"Every einsum — regardless of the number of operands — is decomposed into\npairwise contraction steps along an optimal path (found via whest's\nopt\\_einsum fork).\nThe total cost is the sum of per-step costs:"},"1141":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-133","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-step-cost","content":"For each pairwise step, the **dense** cost is:"},"1142":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-134","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-step-cost","content":"Each fused multiply-add (FMA) counts as 1 operation (see\nConvention above), so the cost of a\ncontraction step is simply the product of all index dimensions — there is\nno factor-of-2 distinction between inner products and outer products."},"1143":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-135","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-step-cost","content":"When symmetry is present, whest reduces each step's cost based on\nthe structure of the contraction."},"1144":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-136","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetric-contraction-cost","content":"Each pairwise step's cost is reduced by two independent multiplicative\nfactors — one for the output (V-side) indices and one for the inner\n(W-side) contracted indices:"},"1145":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-137","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetric-contraction-cost","content":"Each ratio is computed exactly using **Burnside's lemma** over the\npermutation group detected for that step by the\n`SubgraphSymmetryOracle`. For the\nfull symmetric group S$_k$ on $k$ equal-sized axes, Burnside reduces to\nthe stars-and-bars formula $\\binom\\{n+k-1\\}\\{k\\}$; for proper subgroups like\n$C_k$ or block groups the oracle returns the exact generators and\nBurnside counts over the enumerated elements."},"1146":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-138","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetric-contraction-cost","content":"The **output (V-side) reduction** is always applied when the step's\nintermediate has a non-trivial permutation group on its free indices —\nonly the unique output elements need to be computed."},"1147":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-139","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetric-contraction-cost","content":"The **inner (W-side) reduction** is applied only when *all* labels in\nthe detected inner group are present as contracted indices in that\nspecific pairwise step. If any of those labels were contracted at an\nearlier step and no longer appear in the current step, the inner\nreduction is skipped (the per-step table shows this as `[W: ...]` when\ndetected-but-not-applied versus `[W✓: ...]` when applied). Inner\nsymmetry can be toggled globally with\n`we.configure(use_inner_symmetry=False)`."},"1148":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-140","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#symmetric-contraction-cost","content":"The two factors are independent; outer-product contractions (no summed\nindices) and non-uniform index dimensions are handled by the same\nformula, since Burnside's lemma makes no assumption about uniform sizes\nbeyond requiring axes in the same orbit to share a dimension."},"1149":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-141","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#multi-operand-contractions","content":"For a simple two-operand einsum like `'ij,jk->ik'`, there is one step,\nso the total cost equals the step cost. For multi-operand einsums (3+\ntensors), the optimizer finds the pairwise ordering that minimizes the\ntotal cost."},"1150":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-142","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#multi-operand-contractions","content":"When symmetric tensors are present, the optimizer is symmetry-aware: it\nuses symmetric costs to decide which pair to contract at each step, so the\nreturned path may differ from the dense-optimal path. Symmetry propagates\nthrough intermediates — if an early contraction produces a symmetric\nintermediate, subsequent steps benefit from the reduced element count, and\nthe optimizer factors this into its ordering decisions."},"1151":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-143","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#multi-operand-contractions","content":"Use `we.einsum_path()` to inspect the per-step breakdown. See\nUse Einsum for examples."},"1152":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-144","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"The analytical formulas above treat all operations within a category as\nequally expensive -- `exp`, `log`, `sin`, and `abs` all cost\n$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$ FLOPs. In reality, `exp` decomposes into\na minimax polynomial approximation requiring approximately 14 FP\ninstructions per element, while `abs` is a single bit manipulation."},"1153":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-145","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Per-operation **weights** correct for this. Each weight is a multiplicative\nconstant applied on top of the analytical formula:"},"1154":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-146","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Operation"},"1155":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-147","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Analytical formula"},"1156":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-148","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Weight"},"1157":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-149","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Effective cost (256x256)"},"1158":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-150","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`add`"},"1159":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-151","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$"},"1160":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-152","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"1"},"1161":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-153","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"65,536"},"1162":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-154","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`exp`"},"1163":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-155","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$"},"1164":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-156","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"16"},"1165":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-157","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"1,048,576"},"1166":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-158","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`sin`"},"1167":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-159","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$"},"1168":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-160","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"16"},"1169":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-161","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"1,048,576"},"1170":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-162","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`matmul`"},"1171":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-163","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$m \\cdot k \\cdot n$"},"1172":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-164","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"1"},"1173":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-165","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"16,777,216"},"1174":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-166","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`linalg.cholesky`"},"1175":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-167","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$n^3$"},"1176":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-168","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"4"},"1177":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-169","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"67,108,864"},"1178":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-170","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"`reshape`"},"1179":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-171","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$0$"},"1180":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-172","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"0"},"1181":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-173","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"0"},"1182":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-174","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Weights are measured using the overhead-subtracted correction-factor\nmethodology described in FLOP Weight Calibration Results.\nThe formula is:"},"1183":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-175","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"$w(\\text\\{op\\}) = \\max\\bigl(\\alpha_\\{\\text\\{raw\\}\\}(\\text\\{op\\}) - \\text\\{overhead\\}_\\{\\text\\{category\\}\\}, \\ 0\\bigr)$"},"1184":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-176","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"where $\\alpha_\\{\\text\\{raw\\}\\}$ is the median ratio of hardware-observed FP\ninstructions to analytical FLOPs (FMA = 1 op), measured via\n`fp_arith_inst_retired` performance counters. The ufunc dispatch overhead\n(measured from `np.abs`, which generates zero FP arithmetic) is subtracted\nper category to remove numpy implementation noise from the weight."},"1185":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-177","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"BLAS-backed operations (contractions, linalg) have weights near 1.0 because\ntheir tight FMA loops execute almost exactly 1 hardware FP instruction per\nanalytical FLOP, with no ufunc overhead to subtract."},"1186":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-178","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Known analytical zero-FLOP operations (`reshape`, `broadcast_to`,\n`random.seed`, etc.) are stored with weight `0.0` in the official artifacts\nso the generated docs surface them as free rather than as `1x` unit-cost ops."},"1187":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-179","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Integer and bitwise operations (`bitwise_and`, `gcd`, `lcm`, etc.) use the\n`instructions` hardware counter (total retired instructions) because they\ndo not retire `fp_arith_inst_retired` events. Their weights are derived from\ninstruction counts normalized the same way as FP operations."},"1188":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-180","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#per-operation-weights","content":"Official weights are packaged with whest and enabled by default on import.\nUse `WHEST_WEIGHTS_FILE` to override them with a custom JSON file, or set\n`WHEST_DISABLE_WEIGHTS=1` to disable weighting entirely and fall back to\nunit weights (1.0 for all operations)."},"1189":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-181","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-weights-are-applied","content":"Weights are applied centrally in `BudgetContext.deduct()`. Every counted\noperation passes its `op_name` to `deduct()`, which looks up the weight\nand multiplies it into the cost:"},"1190":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-182","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#how-weights-are-applied","content":"This means weights compose with `flop_multiplier` and with symmetry\nreductions -- symmetry reduces the element count, the weight scales the\nper-element cost, and both apply independently."},"1191":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-183","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#overriding-or-disabling-packaged-weights","content":"Normal imports load the packaged official weights automatically. To override\nthem at import time, set `WHEST_WEIGHTS_FILE`:"},"1192":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-184","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#overriding-or-disabling-packaged-weights","content":"To disable weighting entirely and use unit weights instead:"},"1193":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-185","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#overriding-or-disabling-packaged-weights","content":"The JSON file must have a `\"weights\"` key mapping operation names to floats:"},"1194":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-186","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#overriding-or-disabling-packaged-weights","content":"Operations not listed in the override file default to 1.0. See\nCalibrate Weights for how to generate\nthis file."},"1195":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-187","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#where-weights-come-from","content":"Weights can be determined in two ways:"},"1196":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-188","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#where-weights-come-from","content":"**Hardware performance counters** (Linux `perf stat`) -- counts actual\nfloating-point instructions retired by the CPU, weighted by SIMD width.\nThis gives the true number of basic FP ops per high-level operation."},"1197":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-189","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#where-weights-come-from","content":"**Wall-clock time normalization** -- measures `time(op) / time(add)` as\na relative proxy. Less precise than hardware counters but works on any\nplatform."},"1198":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-190","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#where-weights-come-from","content":"The `benchmarks/` package in this repository automates both methods. See\nCalibrate Weights."},"1199":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-191","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#flop-multiplier","content":"The `flop_multiplier` parameter in `BudgetContext` scales all costs:"},"1200":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-192","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#flop-multiplier","content":"This is useful for experimentation or adjusting the difficulty of a budget\nconstraint. Note that `flop_multiplier` and per-operation weights are\nindependent — `flop_multiplier` scales *all* operations uniformly, while\nweights scale each operation individually."},"1201":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-193","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#namespaces","content":"Use `we.namespace(...)` to create nested namespace scopes inside an active `BudgetContext`. The `namespace` parameter on `BudgetContext` sets the root namespace prefix for operations in that context:"},"1202":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-194","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#namespaces","content":"Namespaces are hierarchical and exact per operation. `we.namespace(\"precompute\")` inside `namespace=\"predict\"` records operations as `predict.precompute`, and nested scopes append dotted segments such as `predict.fallback.sampling`."},"1203":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-195","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#namespaces","content":"Namespaces do not create child budgets or separate time limits. They only change attribution. `budget.summary()` and `we.budget_summary()` stay flat by default; `budget.summary(by_namespace=True)` and `we.budget_summary(by_namespace=True)` opt into a `By namespace` section. The structured forms, `budget.summary_dict(by_namespace=True)` and `we.budget_summary_dict(by_namespace=True)`, return the same exact buckets keyed by the full namespace path or `None` for unlabeled operations."},"1204":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-196","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#related-pages","content":"Operation Categories — which operations are free, counted, or unsupported"},"1205":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-197","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#related-pages","content":"Budget Planning — query costs before running"},"1206":{"id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model-198","page_id":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/flop-counting-model#related-pages","content":"Calibrate Weights — measure per-operation weights empirically"},"1207":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"page","content":"How whest Works","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Understanding whest"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works"},"1208":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-0","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"The wrapping pattern"},"1209":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-1","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Cost interception"},"1210":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-2","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"Budget enforcement"},"1211":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-3","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-flow-of-a-single-call","content":"The flow of a single call"},"1212":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-4","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"The operation registry"},"1213":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-5","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"1214":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-6","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"*Understand how whest wraps NumPy to count every FLOP.*"},"1215":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-7","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"**You will learn:**"},"1216":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-8","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"The wrapping pattern that makes `import whest as we` a drop-in for NumPy"},"1217":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-9","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"How costs are calculated from tensor shapes before execution"},"1218":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-10","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"How budgets are enforced and what happens when they are exceeded"},"1219":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-11","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","content":"How the operation registry classifies every NumPy callable"},"1220":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-12","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"whest exposes a NumPy-compatible API. When you write `import whest as we` and call `we.einsum(...)`, you get a function that behaves like `np.einsum(...)` but with FLOP counting layered on top."},"1221":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-13","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"Under the hood, whest re-exports wrapped versions of NumPy functions. The `whest/__init__.py` module imports from internal modules that each handle a category of operations:"},"1222":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-14","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**`_pointwise.py`** -- unary and binary elementwise operations (`exp`, `add`, `multiply`, etc.)"},"1223":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-15","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**`_einsum.py`** -- the `einsum` and `einsum_path` functions with symmetry-aware path optimization"},"1224":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-16","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**`_free_ops.py`** -- zero-cost operations (`zeros`, `reshape`, `transpose`, `copy`, etc.)"},"1225":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-17","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**`_counting_ops.py`** -- operations that look free but involve genuine computation (`trace`, `histogram`, etc.)"},"1226":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-18","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**`_sorting_ops.py`** -- sorting, searching, and set operations"},"1227":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-19","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"**Submodules** -- `whest.linalg`, `whest.fft`, `whest.random`, `whest.stats`"},"1228":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-20","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-wrapping-pattern","content":"Each wrapped function follows the same pattern: compute the analytical FLOP cost, check the budget, then delegate to the real NumPy implementation."},"1229":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-21","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"When you call a counted operation, whest computes its FLOP cost analytically from the tensor shapes *before* the operation executes. The cost depends on the operation category:"},"1230":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-22","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Category"},"1231":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-23","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Cost formula"},"1232":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-24","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Example"},"1233":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-25","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Pointwise unary"},"1234":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-26","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`numel(output)`"},"1235":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-27","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`we.exp(x)` on shape (256, 256) costs 65,536"},"1236":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-28","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Pointwise binary"},"1237":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-29","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`numel(output)`"},"1238":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-30","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`we.add(a, b)` with broadcast output (256, 256) costs 65,536"},"1239":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-31","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Reduction"},"1240":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-32","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`numel(input)`"},"1241":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-33","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`we.sum(x)` on shape (256, 256) costs 65,536"},"1242":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-34","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Einsum"},"1243":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-35","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"product of all index dimensions"},"1244":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-36","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`'ij,jk->ik'` with shapes (m, k), (k, n) costs m \\* k \\* n"},"1245":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-37","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Free"},"1246":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-38","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"0"},"1247":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-39","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"`we.zeros(...)`, `we.reshape(...)`, `we.transpose(...)`"},"1248":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-40","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"The cost is always deterministic -- the same shapes produce the same FLOP count regardless of the data values or the hardware running the code."},"1249":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-41","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#cost-interception","content":"Each FMA (fused multiply-add) counts as 1 operation, not 2. A matrix multiply of dimensions (m, k) x (k, n) costs `m * k * n` FLOPs."},"1250":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-42","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"`BudgetContext` accumulates the cost of every operation that runs inside it. Before each counted operation executes, the budget is checked:"},"1251":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-43","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"The wrapped function computes the analytical cost from input shapes"},"1252":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-44","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"It calls `budget.deduct(op_name, flop_cost=cost, ...)` on the active budget"},"1253":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-45","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"`deduct()` checks if `flops_used + cost > flop_budget`"},"1254":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-46","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"If within budget: the cost is recorded, and the real NumPy function runs"},"1255":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-47","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"If over budget: `BudgetExhaustedError` is raised, and the operation does **not** execute"},"1256":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-48","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"Every deduction is recorded as an `OpRecord` in the budget's operation log, capturing the operation name, input shapes, FLOP cost, and cumulative total. This log powers the budget summary and debugging tools."},"1257":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-49","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#budget-enforcement","content":"If no explicit `BudgetContext` is active, whest automatically creates a global default context with a budget of 1e15 FLOPs (configurable via the `WHEST_DEFAULT_BUDGET` environment variable). This means bare calls outside any `with` block still work and still count FLOPs."},"1258":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-50","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-flow-of-a-single-call","content":"Here is what happens when you call `we.matmul(A, B)` with shapes (100, 200) and (200, 50):"},"1259":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-51","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"The registry (`whest/_registry.py`) is a mapping of every NumPy callable to its classification and cost behavior. Each entry specifies:"},"1260":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-52","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"**Category:** one of `counted_unary`, `counted_binary`, `counted_reduction`, `counted_custom`, `free`, or `blacklisted`"},"1261":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-53","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"**Module:** which NumPy module it belongs to (`numpy`, `numpy.linalg`, `numpy.fft`, etc.)"},"1262":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-54","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"**Notes:** any special behavior or cost formula details"},"1263":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-55","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"The categories determine how costs are calculated:"},"1264":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-56","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Category"},"1265":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-57","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Meaning"},"1266":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-58","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Cost"},"1267":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-59","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`counted_unary`"},"1268":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-60","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Scalar math on each element"},"1269":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-61","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`numel(output)`"},"1270":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-62","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`counted_binary`"},"1271":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-63","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Element-wise binary operation"},"1272":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-64","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`numel(output)`"},"1273":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-65","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`counted_reduction`"},"1274":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-66","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Reduce an array along axes"},"1275":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-67","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`numel(input)`"},"1276":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-68","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`counted_custom`"},"1277":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-69","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Bespoke cost formula"},"1278":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-70","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Varies (e.g., `n * ceil(log2(n))` for sort)"},"1279":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-71","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`free`"},"1280":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-72","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Zero FLOP cost"},"1281":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-73","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"0"},"1282":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-74","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"`blacklisted`"},"1283":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-75","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Intentionally unsupported"},"1284":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-76","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"Raises `AttributeError`"},"1285":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-77","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"**Free operations** include allocation (`zeros`, `ones`, `empty`), shape manipulation (`reshape`, `transpose`, `squeeze`), indexing helpers (`ix_`, `indices`), and metadata queries (`shape`, `ndim`, `size`). These do not touch the budget."},"1286":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-78","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"**Blocked operations** include I/O (`save`, `load`), error state management (`geterr`, `seterr`), and other operations that do not make sense in a FLOP-counted context. Calling a blocked operation raises `AttributeError`."},"1287":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-79","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#the-operation-registry","content":"When per-operation weights are loaded, the analytical cost is multiplied by the operation's weight before deduction. This allows the cost model to reflect that `exp` is more expensive than `abs` in terms of actual hardware instructions, while keeping the base formulas simple and deterministic."},"1288":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-80","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#related-pages","content":"FLOP Counting Model -- detailed cost formulas for every category"},"1289":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-81","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#related-pages","content":"Operation Categories -- which operations are free, counted, or blocked"},"1290":{"id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works-82","page_id":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/how-whest-works#related-pages","content":"Competition Guide -- using budgets in competition"},"1291":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"page","content":"Operation Categories","breadcrumbs":["Documentation","Understanding whest"],"tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories"},"1292":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-0","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories#three-categories","content":"Three categories"},"1293":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-1","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories#free-operations-0-flops","content":"Free operations (0 FLOPs)"},"1294":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-2","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories#counted-operations-cost--0","content":"Counted operations (cost > 0)"},"1295":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-3","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories#blacklisted-operations","content":"Blacklisted operations"},"1296":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-4","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"1297":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-5","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","content":"*Use this page to understand which operations cost FLOPs, which are free, and which are unsupported.*"},"1298":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-6","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","content":"**You will learn:**"},"1299":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-7","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","content":"How to identify free, counted, and blacklisted operations"},"1300":{"id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories-8","page_id":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/operation-categories","content":"What cost formulas apply to each coun