ntent":"Full bipartite graph"},"1354":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-4","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#induced-subgraph-for-subset-a-b","content":"Induced subgraph for subset `{A, B}`"},"1355":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-5","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"The subset-keyed oracle"},"1356":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-6","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-detection-algorithm","content":"The detection algorithm"},"1357":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-7","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#goal","content":"Goal"},"1358":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-8","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#column-fingerprints","content":"Column fingerprints"},"1359":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-9","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"Sigma loop: derive pi from generators"},"1360":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-10","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"Per-tuple vs expression-level symmetry"},"1361":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-11","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#interactive-explorer","content":"Interactive explorer"},"1362":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-12","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"Worked examples"},"1363":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-13","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#v-side-and-w-side","content":"V-side and W-side"},"1364":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-14","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"Exact group detection and Burnside counting"},"1365":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-15","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"Complexity bound"},"1366":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-16","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","type":"heading","tags":[],"url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#related-pages","content":"Related pages"},"1367":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-17","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"*Contributor-level walkthrough of whest's symmetry detection algorithm.*"},"1368":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-18","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"**You will learn:**"},"1369":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-19","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"How the bipartite graph is constructed from einsum subscripts"},"1370":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-20","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"How the subset-keyed oracle detects and caches symmetry lazily"},"1371":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-21","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"How the sigma-loop derives label permutations from row permutations"},"1372":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-22","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"How Burnside's lemma counts unique elements for exact FLOP reduction"},"1373":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-23","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","content":"**TL;DR:** whest detects when an einsum expression has symmetry that allows computing fewer FLOPs. It does this by building a bipartite graph from the einsum subscripts, finding column permutations that preserve the graph structure, and using group theory to count how many unique terms exist. The savings can be dramatic -- a symmetric matrix multiplication can cost half as many FLOPs."},"1374":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-24","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"A multi-operand einsum like `'ij,ai,bj->ab'` is decomposed by opt\\_einsum into\na sequence of pairwise contractions. At each step the optimizer must evaluate\ncandidate pairs -- and it needs to know, for each candidate intermediate, whether\nthe result is symmetric, so it can score it with a reduced cost."},"1375":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-25","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"When operands are `SymmetricTensor`s, their per-operand symmetry is known\nupfront. But there is a second source of symmetry: when the same Python object\nappears at multiple operand positions, the output can be symmetric in index\nlabels contributed by those repeated operands -- even if the operands are dense."},"1376":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-26","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"The naive approach is to rerun a detection procedure at every step for every\ncandidate subset. This is too expensive for large contractions. We want:"},"1377":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-27","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"**Correctness** -- detect all exploitable symmetry without false positives."},"1378":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-28","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"**Memoization** -- compute each intermediate's symmetry at most once."},"1379":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-29","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"**Laziness** -- only evaluate subsets that the path optimizer actually visits."},"1380":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-30","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-problem","content":"Subgraph symmetry detection achieves all three."},"1381":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-31","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"The core data structure is a bipartite graph over the einsum expression."},"1382":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-32","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**Left vertices (U):** One U-vertex per axis of each operand. For a dense\noperand with subscript `\"ai\"`, each axis produces its own U-vertex (two total).\nFor a `SymmetricTensor` with subscript `\"ij\"` and declared symmetry `S_2{i,j}`,\nboth axes still produce separate U-vertices -- per-operand symmetry does not\naffect the graph topology. Instead, per-operand symmetry is handled entirely\nby the expanded sigma-loop (see below), which uses the declared symmetry\ngenerators as an additional source of row permutations."},"1383":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-33","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**Right vertices (labels):** One right vertex per unique index label. Labels are\npartitioned into:"},"1384":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-34","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**V (free labels):** appear in the final output subscript or in operands\noutside the current subset (they \"cross the cut\")."},"1385":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-35","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**W (summed labels):** contracted entirely within the current subset."},"1386":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-36","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**Incidence:** An edge from U-vertex `u` to label `c` has weight equal to the\nmultiplicity of `c` in the axes belonging to U-vertex `u`."},"1387":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-37","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-bipartite-graph","content":"**Identical-operand groups:** Operands that are the same Python object are\ngrouped. These groups are the source of induced symmetry."},"1388":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-38","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"Consider `'ij,ai,bj->ab'` with operands `T, A, B` where `T` is a dense tensor:"},"1389":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-39","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"U-vertices (one per axis):"},"1390":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-40","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(T, 0)` -- label set \\{i}"},"1391":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-41","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(T, 1)` -- label set \\{j}"},"1392":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-42","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(A, 0)` -- label set \\{a}"},"1393":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-43","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(A, 1)` -- label set \\{i}"},"1394":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-44","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(B, 0)` -- label set \\{b}"},"1395":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-45","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"`(B, 1)` -- label set \\{j}"},"1396":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-46","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"Free labels at the top level: \\{a, b} (appear in output `->ab`).\nSummed labels at the top level: \\{i, j} (contracted out)."},"1397":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-47","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-example","content":"No identical operands in this example -- `T`, `A`, and `B` are distinct Python\nobjects."},"1398":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-48","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"Now consider the subset `{A, B}` (positions 1 and 2):"},"1399":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-49","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"U-vertices in subset: `(A, 0)`, `(A, 1)`, `(B, 0)`, `(B, 1)`"},"1400":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-50","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"Labels in subset: \\{a, i, b, j}"},"1401":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-51","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"Labels outside subset (in T): \\{i, j}"},"1402":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-52","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"Crossing labels (in subset AND in outside): \\{i, j}"},"1403":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-53","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"V at this step = \\{a, b} + \\{i, j} = \\{a, b, i, j} (all four -- \\{i,j} cross the cut)"},"1404":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-54","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#full-bipartite-graph","content":"W at this step = \\{} (nothing is summed entirely within \\{A, B})"},"1405":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-55","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#induced-subgraph-for-subset-a-b","content":"When we restrict to subset `{A, B}`, labels `i` and `j` cross the cut (they also\nappear in T, outside the subset), so they move from W to V:"},"1406":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-56","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#induced-subgraph-for-subset-a-b","content":"The incidence matrix M at this subset (rows = U-vertices, columns = V+W):"},"1407":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-57","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"The key invariant is the **pure-in-subset property**: the symmetry of an\nintermediate tensor depends only on the set of original operands it was formed\nfrom, not on the order in which they were contracted. This is because:"},"1408":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-58","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"The bipartite graph structure is fixed for the full einsum."},"1409":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-59","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"The induced subgraph on a subset `S` is fully determined by which operands\nare in `S`."},"1410":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-60","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"Symmetry is a property of the final intermediate, not its contraction history."},"1411":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-61","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#the-subset-keyed-oracle","content":"This property makes the subset key canonical. The oracle stores results in a\n`dict[frozenset[int], SubsetSymmetry]` and returns cached results on\nsubsequent calls with the same subset."},"1412":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-62","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#goal","content":"For a fixed subset `S` with incidence matrix `M`, we want the full group\nof **automorphisms of the labelled bipartite graph** -- pairs `(sigma, pi)`\nwhere sigma permutes identical-operand rows and pi permutes label columns,\nsuch that applying `pi` to the columns of `sigma(M)` recovers `M`:"},"1413":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-63","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#goal","content":"Every such `pi` is a symmetry of the intermediate tensor built from `S`.\nRestricted to V labels it contributes to the output (V-side) symmetry;\nrestricted to W labels it contributes to the inner (W-side) symmetry.\nThe V/W partition is part of the labelled structure, so legitimate\nautomorphisms must preserve it -- `pi(V) is a subset of V` and `pi(W) is a subset of W` -- and any\n`pi` with a cycle crossing V to W is rejected."},"1414":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-64","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#column-fingerprints","content":"For each label `c`, compute its column fingerprint `col(c)` -- the tuple of\nincidence values down the rows of M. Labels with identical fingerprints are\n*candidates* for symmetry equivalence. The fingerprint-to-label mapping is\nused by the sigma-loop to derive pi in O(1) per label via hash lookup."},"1415":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-65","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#column-fingerprints","content":"Earlier versions had a standalone fast path that detected S\\_k whenever\nlabels shared a fingerprint, without running the sigma-loop. This was\nincorrect for non-S\\_k groups (see the C3 bug note below) and has been\nremoved. Fingerprints are now used only for pi derivation inside the\nsigma-loop -- they are not a standalone detection mechanism."},"1416":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-66","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"The sigma-loop iterates over **generators** of the row-permutation group on M,\ndrawn from two sources:"},"1417":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-67","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"**Source A -- per-operand internal symmetry generators.** For each operand\nthat carries a declared `PermutationGroup`, each generator of that group is\nlifted to a row permutation on M (permuting only the rows belonging to that\noperand). This captures symmetry that was previously handled by orbit-based\naxis merging."},"1418":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-68","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"**Source B -- identical-operand swap generators.** For each group of k\nidentical operands (same Python object), the k-1 adjacent transpositions\n`(op_i, op_{i+1})` are used as generators. Each such swap is lifted to a row\npermutation that exchanges the rows of the two operands."},"1419":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-69","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"All generators are collected and passed to Dimino's algorithm to build the\nfull row-permutation group. The sigma-loop then iterates over **all elements**\nof this group (not just the generators), deriving pi for each."},"1420":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-70","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"> **Historical note.** An earlier draft emitted a third generator source\n> (**Source C**: coordinated W-axis relabeling across identical operands\n> sharing the same subscript). That source produces **expression-level**\n> symmetries -- valid under dummy-variable renaming of summed indices -- but\n> *not* **per-tuple** symmetries. Feeding them into Burnside orbit compression\n> caused over-compression: on Frobenius `'ij,ij→'` with generic A at n=2, the\n> engine claimed μ=3 when the truth is μ=4. Source C was removed; expression-\n> level symmetries are now recovered separately via $V_{\\text{sub}} \\times S(W)$ (below)\n> without contaminating compression."},"1421":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-71","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"For each group element `sigma`:"},"1422":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-72","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"Lift `sigma` to a row permutation on M."},"1423":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-73","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"Compute `sigma(M)`'s column fingerprints: `sigma * col(c)` for each label `c`."},"1424":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-74","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"**Derive the induced label permutation pi directly.** For each label `l`,\n`pi(l)` is the label whose M-column matches `sigma(M)`'s column for `l` -- a\nhash-table lookup in O(1). When multiple labels share a fingerprint\n(collision), pick the lex-first unused candidate. If any label has no\nmatch, reject this sigma."},"1425":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-75","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"**Validate pi:** require a bijective fingerprint match. In the JS\nexplorer, cross-V/W cycles are retained — a declared axis symmetry that\nlinks a V-axis with a W-axis (e.g., a symmetric matrix used as `A[i,j]`\nwith `i` free and `j` summed) produces a legitimate per-tuple symmetry\neven though it crosses the V/W boundary. The classification tree\n(singleton, young, directProduct, bruteForceOrbit) dispatches correctly\nbased on whether cross elements are present."},"1426":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-76","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"**Collect pi as a `Permutation` object** over all labels. Non-identity\npermutations become generators of the detected per-tuple group $G_{\\text{pt}}$."},"1427":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-77","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#sigma-loop-derive-pi-from-generators","content":"The sigma-loop collects all non-identity pi as `Permutation` objects.\nThese generators are passed to Dimino's algorithm (via `PermutationGroup(...)`)\nto close the group and build the exact **per-tuple** symmetry group."},"1428":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-78","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"Every einsum actually admits **two** distinct label-permutation groups:"},"1429":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-79","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"**Per-tuple** $G_{\\text{pt}}$: a permutation π such that for every tuple `t` of\nindex values, `summand(t) = summand(π⁻¹ t)`. Compression uses this group\n— reusing one orbit representative is only valid when every tuple in the\norbit has the same summand value."},"1430":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-80","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"**Expression-level** $G_{\\text{expr}}$: a permutation π such that the total sum\nis unchanged under renaming all labels by π, even if individual terms get\nreshuffled. Always a superset of $G_{\\text{pt}}$; includes dummy-rename\npermutations of summed labels."},"1431":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-81","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"The expression-level group factors cleanly (when restricted to V/W-\npreserving elements) as $V_{\\text{sub}} \\times S(W)$:"},"1432":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-82","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"$V_{\\text{sub}}$: $G_{\\text{pt}}$ projected to V-labels (the action on output axes)."},"1433":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-83","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"$S(W)$: the full symmetric group on W-labels. Every permutation of W\nis always an expression-level symmetry because summing over W is\nbound-variable iteration — renaming dummies does not change the total."},"1434":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-84","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"$G_{\\text{expr}}$ is computed directly from this formula, with no additional σ-loop\nsource and no Dimino pass. The explorer shows both groups in its sticky\nbar (`per-tuple` and `expr-level` badges) when they differ."},"1435":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-85","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#per-tuple-vs-expression-level-symmetry","content":"**Why both?** Compression formulas (μ, α) must use $G_{\\text{pt}}$ — feeding them\n$G_{\\text{expr}}$ over-compresses, because dummy-rename orbits contain tuples whose\nsummand values differ. But the expression-level group is the \"natural\"\ncounting symmetry readers recognize: bilinear-trace has a Z₂ × Z₂ counting\nsymmetry even though only its Z₂ diagonal is per-tuple. Exposing both\ndistinguishes the *structural* story from the *compression-valid* story."},"1436":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-86","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#interactive-explorer","content":"Walk through each detection step interactively with the Symmetry Explorer — choose a preset example or define your own einsum expression."},"1437":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-87","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"Click to expand each example."},"1438":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-88","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"Consider two identical dense matrices `X`. The bipartite graph has one\nU-vertex per axis (four total), one label per column, and no W-labels\n(nothing is contracted):"},"1439":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-89","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"The incidence matrix M is the 4x4 identity. The only nontrivial sigma swaps\noperands 0 and 1, permuting rows (0 with 2, 1 with 3). Matching sigma(M) columns\nback to M columns gives:"},"1440":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-90","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"So pi = (a c)(b d). Two disjoint 2-cycles from one sigma. The result is\n&#x2A;*block S\\_2: `{(a,b), (c,d)}`**."},"1441":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-91","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"This computes X^T X, which is symmetric. U-vertices:"},"1442":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-92","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"`(X0, 0)` -- label `i`, `(X0, 1)` -- label `a`"},"1443":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-93","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"`(X1, 0)` -- label `i`, `(X1, 1)` -- label `b`"},"1444":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-94","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"Labels: V = `{a, b}` (output), W = `{i}` (contracted). Swapping operands\ngives:"},"1445":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-95","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"Cycle structure on V: single 2-cycle (a b) -- &#x2A;*per-index `S_2{a, b}`**.\nX^T X is symmetric in its two output indices, as expected."},"1446":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-96","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"`einsum('ijk,jki->ik', T, T)` with C3 symmetry declared on T was falsely\ndetected as having `S_2{i,k}` output symmetry. The root cause was orbit-based\naxis merging in the bipartite graph construction."},"1447":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-97","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"C3 acting on \\{i,j,k} has a single orbit \\{i,j,k}, so all three axes were\nmerged into one U-vertex per operand. With merged vertices, labels `i` and\n`k` received identical column fingerprints, and the fingerprint fast path\npromoted them to `S_2{i,k}`. However, C3 contains only 3-cycles -- no\ntranspositions -- so the 2-cycle (i k) is not a valid automorphism."},"1448":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-98","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"The fix has two parts:"},"1449":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-99","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"**Removed orbit-based merging.** Each axis now gets its own U-vertex\nregardless of declared symmetry. This ensures that the graph topology\nfaithfully reflects the actual incidence structure."},"1450":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-100","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#worked-examples","content":"**Expanded the sigma-loop.** Per-operand symmetry generators are fed\ndirectly into the sigma-loop (Source A) alongside identical-operand\nswap generators (Source B). Dimino's algorithm closes the group from the\ndiscovered pi generators, producing C3 (not S2) for this case."},"1451":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-101","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#v-side-and-w-side","content":"V-side groups are symmetries of the output tensor -- they reduce the number of\nunique output elements that need to be computed. W-side groups are symmetries\namong the contracted (summed) labels -- they reduce the number of unique\nsummation terms. Both contribute multiplicatively to the cost reduction:"},"1452":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-102","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#v-side-and-w-side","content":"The **output (V-side) reduction** is always applied when the step's\nintermediate has a non-trivial permutation group on its free indices."},"1453":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-103","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#v-side-and-w-side","content":"The **inner (W-side) reduction** is applied only when *all* labels in\nthe detected inner group are present as contracted indices in that\nspecific pairwise step. If any of those labels were contracted at an\nearlier step and no longer appear, the inner reduction is skipped.\nIn the contraction path table, `[W checkmark: ...]` indicates the inner reduction was\napplied, while `[W: ...]` indicates it was detected but not applied.\nInner symmetry can be toggled with `we.configure(use_inner_symmetry=False)`."},"1454":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-104","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"The sigma-loop collects all valid pi permutations as `Permutation`\nobjects (generators) and builds a `PermutationGroup` directly."},"1455":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-105","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"When the generated group equals S\\_k (the full symmetric group, checked via\n`order == k!`), the existing stars-and-bars formula `C(n+k-1, k)` applies.\nWhen the group is a proper subgroup (e.g., C\\_3 from `einsum('ij,jk,ki->', A, A, A)`),\nBurnside's lemma gives the exact unique element count."},"1456":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-106","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"For `einsum('ij,jk,ki->', A, A, A)` with the same n x n matrix A:"},"1457":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-107","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"The sigma-loop tries all 6 permutations of `{operand 0, 1, 2}`"},"1458":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-108","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"Only 3 produce valid pi's: identity, (i to j to k), (i to k to j)"},"1459":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-109","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"These are the generators of C\\_3 (cyclic group of order 3)"},"1460":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-110","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"Burnside counting on W-labels `{i,j,k}` with dimension n:"},"1461":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-111","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"Identity: n^3 fixed tuples (every tuple is fixed)"},"1462":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-112","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"3-cycle (ijk): n fixed tuples (only i=j=k tuples)"},"1463":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-113","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"3-cycle (ikj): n fixed tuples"},"1464":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-114","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"Total: (n^3 + 2n) / 3"},"1465":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-115","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#exact-group-detection-and-burnside-counting","content":"For n=10: 340 unique elements instead of 220 (S\\_3), giving a more accurate\n(higher) FLOP estimate."},"1466":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-116","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"The oracle evaluates each subset at most once. For a contract with `N` operands\nand groups of sizes `k_1, k_2, ...`:"},"1467":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-117","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"**Generator collection:** Source A contributes O(rank) generators per operand\nwith declared symmetry. Source B contributes k-1 generators per identical group.\nTotal generators: `g = O(N * rank)`."},"1468":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-118","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"**Group enumeration:** Dimino's algorithm builds the full row-permutation\ngroup from the generators in `O(|G| * g)` compositions."},"1469":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-119","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"**Pi derivation:** For each of the `|G|` group elements, deriving pi costs\n`O(n_labels)` via fingerprint hash lookup."},"1470":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-120","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"**Per-subset total:** `O(|G| * (g + n_labels))`."},"1471":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-121","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"**Number of subsets visited:** at most `2^N` (usually much less -- path\nalgorithms visit only O(N^2) subsets in practice)."},"1472":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-122","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#complexity-bound","content":"For the common case of a single pair of identical operands (`|G| = 2`, `g = 1`):\nper-subset cost is `O(n_labels)`."},"1473":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-123","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection#related-pages","content":"Symmetry Savings -- practical guide to using symmetry"},"1474":{"id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection-124","page_id":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-detection","tags":[],"type":"text","url":"/docs/understanding/symmetry-det