62,"1431":1268,"1432":477,"1433":476,"1434":443,"1435":175,"1436":1385,"1437":632,"1438":664,"1439":1274,"1440":1199,"1441":1312,"1442":230,"1443":231,"1444":972,"1445":695,"1446":259,"1447":610,"1448":1270,"1449":118,"1450":59,"1451":1375,"1452":1247,"1453":1245,"1454":1294,"1455":1425,"1456":790,"1457":1296,"1458":1038,"1459":1308,"1460":607,"1461":910,"1462":512,"1463":513,"1464":1333,"1465":802,"1466":1284,"1467":77,"1468":79,"1469":109,"1470":106,"1471":100,"1472":809,"1473":1230,"1474":782,"1475":1223,"1476":345,"1477":1040},"orderedDocs":[[1063,"(256, 256, k=10) → 655,360"],[1069,"(256, 256) @ (256, 256) → 256³"],[1066,"(256, 256) solve → 16,777,216"],[1225,"**`_counting_ops.py`** -- operations that look free but involve genuine computation (`trace`, `histogram`, etc.)"],[1223,"**`_einsum.py`** -- the `einsum` and `einsum_path` functions with symmetry-aware path optimization"],[1224,"**`_free_ops.py`** -- zero-cost operations (`zeros`, `reshape`, `transpose`, `copy`, etc.)"],[1222,"**`_pointwise.py`** -- unary and binary elementwise operations (`exp`, `add`, `multiply`, etc.)"],[1226,"**`_sorting_ops.py`** -- sorting, searching, and set operations"],[31,"**`bitmap_to_subset` in DP now correctly handles operand renumbering.**\nPreviously, when `_dp_parse_out_single_term_ops` removed or renumbered\noperands before the DP loop (e.g., on `einsum('i,ab,cd->abcd', v, X, X)`\nwhere `v` has a unique index that reduces to a scalar), the\nbitmap-to-subset mapping would point at the wrong original operand\npositions, causing the oracle to return symmetry for an unrelated\nintermediate. This bug was latent under the conservative 2× heuristic\nand only surfaces with exact ratio scoring."],[45,"**`budget_live()`** — Rich-based live-updating budget display context manager"],[46,"**`einsum_path()`** — inspect contraction plans with per-step symmetry savings without spending budget"],[19,"**`matvec` and `vecmat`** — new FLOP-counted wrappers for NumPy 2.2's matrix-vector\nand vector-matrix product ufuncs. Cost = `output_size * contracted_axis` (weight 1.0)."],[16,"**`TimeExhaustedError`** added to both the core library and the client package."],[20,"**`UnsupportedFunctionError`** — new exception for calling functions that require a\nnewer NumPy version than what's installed."],[44,"**`WHEST_DEFAULT_BUDGET` env var** — configure the global default budget amount"],[134,"**1. A global default budget is active automatically — use `BudgetContext` for control.**"],[136,"**2. Know what's free and what's counted.**"],[142,"**3. Use `we.flops.*` to estimate costs before running.**"],[362,"**331**"],[144,"**4. Use `we.einsum` as the primary computation primitive.**"],[146,"**5. Use `wall_time_limit_s` for time-limited execution.**"],[149,"**6. Exploit symmetry for cost savings.**"],[361,"**7,363**"],[47,"**90%+ test coverage gate** enforced in CI"],[747,"**After (whest) — simplest form:**"],[748,"**After (whest) — with explicit budget control:**"],[391,"**Array subclass with `__array_ufunc__`**: Would intercept ufunc calls, but whest arrays are plain `numpy.ndarray` by design -- no custom tensor class."],[937,"**Arrays stay on the server.** The client holds lightweight `RemoteArray` handles that reference server-side data. When you call `we.einsum(...)`, the client sends the operation and handle IDs to the server, which executes it and returns a new handle."],[746,"**Before (NumPy):**"],[910,"**Binary pointwise ops** use intersection of both operands' groups after\nbroadcast alignment"],[1055,"**Binary** (add, multiply, ...)"],[1100,"**Bincount**"],[1344,"**Blacklisted categories:** I/O (`save`, `load`, `loadtxt`, `savetxt`, `savez`, `genfromtxt`), configuration (`seterr`, `geterr`, `setbufsize`), datetime (`busday_count`, `is_busday`), display (`array2string`, `array_repr`), functional (`apply_along_axis`, `piecewise`, `frompyfunc`)."],[1286,"**Blocked operations** include I/O (`save`, `load`), error state management (`geterr`, `seterr`), and other operations that do not make sense in a FLOP-counted context. Calling a blocked operation raises `AttributeError`."],[429,"**Budget / Used / Remaining:** the top rows show the explicit competition budget, current spend, and remaining headroom"],[938,"**Budget enforcement happens server-side.** The client cannot manipulate FLOP counts."],[430,"**By namespace:** `solver` is the root prefix, and nested scopes show up as dotted paths like `solver.precompute`. Use `budget.summary(by_namespace=True)` for the current context or `we.budget_summary(by_namespace=True)` for the accumulated session/global view"],[431,"**By operation:** this toy pass is dominated by the single `einsum`; `exp` and `sum` are tiny by comparison"],[1260,"**Category:** one of `counted_unary`, `counted_binary`, `counted_reduction`, `counted_custom`, `free`, or `blacklisted`"],[435,"**Check costs before committing budget.** Use cost query functions to estimate before executing:"],[21,"**CI NumPy version matrix** — tests now run against NumPy 2.0, 2.1, and 2.2."],[42,"**Client-server architecture** — `whest-client` and `whest-server` packages for sandboxed competition evaluation over ZMQ"],[936,"**Client** is a drop-in replacement (`import whest as we`) that proxies every operation to the server over ZMQ (msgpack-encoded messages)."],[1426,"**Collect pi as a `Permutation` object** over all labels. Non-identity\npermutations become generators of the detected per-tuple group $G_{\\text{pt}}$."],[1038,"**Composable:** You can sum individual operation costs to predict total cost"],[999,"**Container-level (hard):** The Docker container enforces a kernel-level time limit via cgroups/rlimit. If the in-library check doesn't catch the overshoot (e.g., a single very long numpy call), the container delivers `SIGKILL`. This is the ultimate backstop — no Python code can escape it."],[1377,"**Correctness** -- detect all exploitable symmetry without false positives."],[1136,"**Declared per-operand symmetry.** When an operand is wrapped with\n`we.as_symmetric()`, its symmetry groups are embedded in the bipartite\ngraph as U-vertex equivalence classes. These propagate into intermediate\ntensors automatically."],[941,"**Default endpoint:** `ipc:///tmp/whest.sock` (configurable via `WHEST_SERVER_URL`)"],[1424,"**Derive the induced label permutation pi directly.** For each label `l`,\n`pi(l)` is the label whose M-column matches `sigma(M)`'s column for `l` -- a\nhash-table lookup in O(1). When multiple labels share a fingerprint\n(collision), pick the lex-first unused candidate. If any label has no\nmatch, reject this sigma."],[1128,"**Det / Slogdet**"],[1035,"**Deterministic:** The same code always produces the same FLOP count, regardless of hardware"],[1067,"**Dot / Matmul**"],[17,"**Einsum path caching.** Contraction paths are now cached in a module-level\nLRU cache (default 4096 entries). Repeated `we.einsum()` calls with the same\nsubscripts, shapes, optimizer, and symmetry structure reuse the cached path\ninstead of recomputing it. New public API: `we.clear_einsum_cache()`,\n`we.einsum_cache_info()`, and `we.configure(einsum_path_cache_size=N)`."],[1049,"**Einsum**"],[1122,"**Einsum** (symmetric contraction)"],[33,"**Enriched `PathInfo` display** — `we.einsum_path().format_table(verbose=False)`\n(called by `__str__`) now shows an `Optimizer:` header line resolving\n`optimize='auto'`/`'auto-hq'` to the inner choice that actually ran\n(e.g. `optimal`, `dynamic_programming`, `random_greedy_128`), a\n`contract` column giving the path-supplied contraction tuple, and a\n`unique/dense` column showing the bare element counts that the\nsymmetry savings derive from. Call `format_table(verbose=True)` for an\nindented detail row per step showing the merged operand subset, the\nintermediate's output shape, and the running cumulative cost — the\nmost useful view when debugging why a particular step's savings are\nwhat they are."],[25,"**Every optimizer is symmetry-aware** — the `symmetry_oracle` kwarg is plumbed\nthrough `_PATH_OPTIONS` so that optimal, branch-\\*, greedy, random-greedy, and\ndynamic-programming algorithms all receive symmetry information and use the\nexact `unique/dense` ratio for scoring. DP uses a subset-keyed ratio cache\n(`get_ratio(s, legs)`) co-located with the existing `bitmap_to_subset` closure\ninside `DynamicProgramming.__call__`, amortizing the int↔str label translation\nacross all `_dp_compare_*` helper calls for a given subset. Previously only\ngreedy received symmetry info in some code paths."],[1304,"**Examples:** `zeros`, `ones`, `full`, `eye`, `arange`, `linspace`, `empty`, `reshape`, `transpose`, `concatenate`, `stack`, `split`, `squeeze`, `expand_dims`, `ravel`, `take`, `where`, `copy`, `astype`, `asarray`"],[1450,"**Expanded the sigma-loop.** Per-operand symmetry generators are fed\ndirectly into the sigma-loop (Source A) alongside identical-operand\nswap generators (Source B). Dimino's algorithm closes the group from the\ndiscovered pi generators, producing C3 (not S2) for this case."],[437,"**Exploit symmetry for savings.** If your tensors are symmetric, wrapping them with `we.as_symmetric()` can halve pointwise costs and significantly reduce einsum costs. See Symmetry Savings for details."],[523,"**Exploit symmetry.** If operands are symmetric, use `we.as_symmetric()` to halve pointwise costs and significantly reduce einsum costs. See Symmetry Savings."],[1430,"**Expression-level** $G_{\\text{expr}}$: a permutation π such that the total sum\nis unchanged under renaming all labels by π, even if individual terms get\nreshuffled. Always a superset of $G_{\\text{pt}}$; includes dummy-rename\npermutations of summed labels."],[41,"**FFT module** — `fft`, `ifft`, `rfft`, `irfft`, `fft2`, `ifft2`, `fftn`, `ifftn`, `rfftn`, `irfftn` and free helpers (`fftfreq`, `rfftfreq`, `fftshift`, `ifftshift`)"],[618,"**Fix:** `rfft` costs half as much. If your input is real-valued, always prefer `rfft`/`irfft` over `fft`/`ifft`."],[774,"**Fix:** 32 operations are blacklisted because they are I/O, configuration, or datetime functions with no FLOP cost. See Operation Categories for the full list. Use `numpy` directly for these."],[1004,"**Fix:** Change the port in both the server `--url` and client `WHEST_SERVER_URL`."],[569,"**Fix:** Check all index dimensions. A subscript like `'ijkl,jklm->im'` multiplies all five dimension sizes together. Use `we.flops.einsum_cost()` or `we.einsum_path()` to preview costs before executing."],[1002,"**Fix:** Ensure the server is running before starting the client. Check that `WHEST_SERVER_URL` matches the server's `--url` argument."],[776,"**Fix:** If you import NumPy alongside whest, make sure to use `we.` for operations you want counted. Operations called through `np.` bypass FLOP counting entirely."],[727,"**Fix:** Operations called through `numpy` directly bypass FLOP counting. Always use `we.linalg.*`."],[620,"**Fix:** The cost scales as $5 \\cdot \\prod n_\\{i\\} \\cdot \\lceil\\log_2(\\prod n_\\{i\\})\\rceil$. A 256x256 2-D FFT processes 65,536 elements, not 256. Use `fft_cost` to estimate before running."],[455,"**Fix:** whest supports NumPy `>=2.0.0,<2.3.0` (default install uses NumPy 2.2). Using `uv` handles this automatically. If you installed manually, check your NumPy version:"],[433,"**Flat default:** the default summary stays flat unless you opt into `by_namespace=True`"],[472,"**Flat default:** the summary stays flat unless you explicitly ask for `we.budget_summary(by_namespace=True)`"],[1285,"**Free operations** include allocation (`zeros`, `ones`, `empty`), shape manipulation (`reshape`, `transpose`, `squeeze`), indexing helpers (`ix_`, `indices`), and metadata queries (`shape`, `ndim`, `size`). These do not touch the budget."],[1070,"**Free ops**"],[1467,"**Generator collection:** Source A contributes O(rank) generators per operand\nwith declared symmetry. Source B contributes k-1 generators per identical group.\nTotal generators: `g = O(N * rank)`."],[43,"**Global default budget** — a 1e15 FLOP budget auto-activates on first use, so explicit `BudgetContext` is no longer required for quick scripts"],[1468,"**Group enumeration:** Dimino's algorithm builds the full row-permutation\ngroup from the generators in `O(|G| * g)` compositions."],[1196,"**Hardware performance counters** (Linux `perf stat`) -- counts actual\nfloating-point instructions retired by the CPU, weighted by SIMD width.\nThis gives the true number of basic FP ops per high-level operation."],[1036,"**Hardware-independent:** A matmul costs the same FLOPs on a laptop and a server"],[32,"**Heterogeneous block dimensions in `unique_elements`** — the stars-and-bars\nblock-cardinality calculation assumed all axes within a block had the same\ndimension. For rectangular block-symmetric tensors (e.g.\n`einsum('ab,cd->abcd', X, X)` with `X` of shape `(3, 4)`), it computed\n`n**s = 3**2 = 9` instead of the correct product `3*4 = 12`, silently\nunderestimating the unique-element count by up to \\~8× on rank-3 cases.\n`block_card` is now computed as `prod(size_dict[c] for c in blocks[0])`,\nwhich reduces to the old formula for per-index groups and gives the\ncorrect product for block groups with differing axis sizes."],[1097,"**Histogram**"],[1387,"**Identical-operand groups:** Operands that are the same Python object are\ngrouped. These groups are the source of induced symmetry."],[998,"**In-library (cooperative):** `BudgetContext(wall_time_limit_s=N)` checks the deadline before and after each numpy call. When exceeded, it raises `TimeExhaustedError` with diagnostic info (which operation, elapsed time, configured limit). This is a UX feature — it gives participants a clean error message."],[1386,"**Incidence:** An edge from U-vertex `u` to label `c` has weight equal to the\nmultiplicity of `c` in the axes belonging to U-vertex `u`."],[525,"**Increase budget.** If the computation is genuinely needed and you have headroom, raise `flop_budget` on the `BudgetContext`."],[1137,"**Induced symmetry from repeated operands.** When the same Python object\nis passed at multiple operand positions, the subgraph oracle detects this\nvia Python identity (`is`) and derives symmetry groups on the output that\ncannot be seen from per-operand metadata alone."],[556,"**Input symmetry** — wrap with `we.as_symmetric()` before passing to einsum. The optimizer automatically uses symmetry to choose the best contraction order and charges reduced costs:"],[1131,"**Inv**"],[1379,"**Laziness** -- only evaluate subsets that the path optimizer actually visits."],[1382,"**Left vertices (U):** One U-vertex per axis of each operand. For a dense\noperand with subscript `\"ai\"`, each axis produces its own U-vertex (two total).\nFor a `SymmetricTensor` with subscript `\"ij\"` and declared symmetry `S_2{i,j}`,\nboth axes still produce separate U-vertices -- per-operand symmetry does not\naffect the graph topology. Instead, per-operand symmetry is handled entirely\nby the expanded sigma-loop (see below), which uses the declared symmetry\ngenerators as an additional source of row permutations."],[1079,"**Lexsort**"],[1378,"**Memoization** -- compute each intermediate's symmetry at most once."],[1261,"**Module:** which NumPy module it belongs to (`numpy`, `numpy.linalg`, `numpy.fft`, etc.)"],[393,"**Monkeypatching with frozen numpy**: Simple, works with NumPy's existing test infrastructure, tests exactly what users experience (same function signatures), and the frozen-numpy trick prevents infinite recursion."],[18,"**Multi-version NumPy support.** whest now supports NumPy 2.0, 2.1, and 2.2\n(`>=2.0.0,<2.3.0`). Default install resolves to NumPy 2.2. Functions not available\nin older NumPy versions raise `UnsupportedFunctionError` with an actionable message\nat call time (not import time)."],[34,"**New `PathInfo.optimizer_used: str`** field and new `StepInfo` fields\n`path_indices: tuple[int, ...]` and `merged_subset: frozenset[int] | None`.\nThe `merged_subset` field is the exact key\n`SubgraphSymmetryOracle.sym(...)` uses for its lookups, making the\nsymmetry column directly attributable to the oracle's view of each\nintermediate."],[1262,"**Notes:** any special behavior or cost formula details"],[1471,"**Number of subsets visited:** at most `2^N` (usually much less -- path\nalgorithms visit only O(N^2) subsets in practice)."],[38,"**NumPy compatibility test harness** — run NumPy's own test suite against whest via monkeypatching; 7,300+ tests passing across 7 NumPy test modules"],[473,"**Operations table:** the 10-layer MLP spreads FLOPs roughly equally across `random.randn`, `multiply`, `array`, and `einsum` (\\~25% each); activations (`maximum`) are comparatively cheap, and the Kaiming scale `sqrt` adds just 1 FLOP"],[557,"**Output symmetry** — pass `symmetric_axes` to `einsum()` to declare that the result is symmetric. This wraps the output as a `SymmetricTensor` so downstream operations benefit from reduced costs. It does NOT affect the cost of this einsum — it's a declaration about the result's structure:"],[1082,"**Partition**"],[15,"**Per-operation duration tracking.** Every operation now records its wall-clock\nduration in `OpRecord.duration`. The budget summary (both plain-text and Rich)\nshows wall time, tracked/untracked breakdown, and per-operation timing. Use\n`budget.summary()` or `we.budget_summary()` to see the timing data."],[1470,"**Per-subset total:** `O(|G| * (g + n_labels))`."],[1429,"**Per-tuple** $G_{\\text{pt}}$: a permutation π such that for every tuple `t` of\nindex values, `summand(t) = summand(π⁻¹ t)`. Compression uses this group\n— reusing one orbit representative is only valid when every tuple in the\norbit has the same summand value."],[220,"**perf**"],[1469,"**Pi derivation:** For each of the `|G|` group elements, deriving pi costs\n`O(n_labels)` via fingerprint hash lookup."],[1116,"**Pointwise** (unary/binary)"],[39,"**Polynomial operations** — `polyval`, `polyfit`, `polymul`, `polydiv`, `polyadd`, `polysub`, `poly`, `roots`, `polyder`, `polyint` with analytical FLOP costs"],[438,"**Prefer cheaper operations.** A matrix-vector product via `we.einsum('ij,j->i', A, x)` costs `m*n` FLOPs, while a full matrix-matrix multiply costs `m*n*k`. Avoid computing more than you need."],[470,"**Reading the output:**"],[522,"**Reduce dimensions.** If `random.randn(1024, 1024)` is too expensive, try smaller arrays. A 512x512 matrix costs 1/4 the FLOPs of a 1024x1024 matrix for a matmul."],[1119,"**Reduction**"],[1058,"**Reduction** (sum, mean, max, ...)"],[909,"**Reductions** use the setwise stabilizer of the reduced axes"],[1449,"**Removed orbit-based merging.** Each axis now gets its own U-vertex\nregardless of declared symmetry. This ensures that the graph topology\nfaithfully reflects the actual incidence structure."],[22,"**Renamed package from `mechestim` to `whest`** to reflect the new challenge\nname \"ARC Whitebox Estimation Challenge\". The import convention changes from\n`import mechestim as me` to `import whest as we`."],[1037,"**Reproducible:** No variance from CPU scheduling, cache effects, or thermal throttling"],[1383,"**Right vertices (labels):** One right vertex per unique index label. Labels are\npartitioned into:"],[392,"**Running tests with `import whest as np`**: NumPy's test files import from `numpy._core`, `numpy.testing`, etc. -- can't redirect all internal imports."],[1085,"**Searchsorted**"],[940,"**Serialization:** msgpack with binary-safe array payloads"],[935,"**Server** runs the real whest library backed by NumPy. It stores all arrays, enforces budgets, and counts FLOPs."],[1091,"**Set ops**"],[1109,"**Shuffle / Permutation**"],[26,"**Silent fallback deleted** — the previous code silently fell back to dense\ncosts when detection produced no result. The oracle now enforces that symmetry\ninformation is consumed. Enforcement is verified by\n`tests/test_no_silent_symmetry_drop.py`."],[1106,"**Simple samplers**"],[908,"**Slicing** uses the pointwise stabilizer of the removed axes"],[1064,"**Solve**"],[1125,"**Solve**"],[1076,"**Sort / Argsort**"],[1417,"**Source A -- per-operand internal symmetry generators.** For each operand\nthat carries a declared `PermutationGroup`, each generator of that group is\nlifted to a row permutation on M (permuting only the rows belonging to that\noperand). This captures symmetry that was previously handled by orbit-based\naxis merging."],[1418,"**Source B -- identical-operand swap generators.** For each group of k\nidentical operands (same Python object), the k-1 adjacent transpositions\n`(op_i, op_{i+1})` are used as generators. Each such swap is lifted to a row\npermutation that exchanges the rows of the two operands."],[526,"**Split into phases.** Use namespaces to attribute different phases without splitting the FLOP budget into child budgets:"],[1227,"**Submodules** -- `whest.linalg`, `whest.fft`, `whest.random`, `whest.stats`"],[1061,"**SVD**"],[23,"**Symmetric BLAS classification restored.** Pairwise contractions with\nsymmetric inputs now correctly report `SYMM`, `SYMV`, or `SYDT` BLAS\ntypes instead of the generic `GEMM`, `GEMV`, `DOT`. This was disabled\nduring the subgraph-symmetry refactor because per-input symmetry wasn't\nbeing looked up; now each step's inputs are queried via\n`symmetry_oracle.sym(ssa_to_subset[ssa_id])` before calling `can_blas`."],[24,"**Symmetry detection rewritten** — the induced-symmetry mechanism is replaced\nby a subset-keyed subgraph symmetry oracle (`SubgraphSymmetryOracle`). The\noracle analyses the bipartite structure of the einsum expression, evaluates\nsymmetry lazily per operand subset, and caches results. This correctly handles\nintermediates (not just the top-level contraction) and eliminates over-eager\nper-step propagation."],[37,"**Symmetry-aware path finding** — the opt\\_einsum path optimizer now factors symmetry savings into contraction ordering decisions, producing different (cheaper) paths for symmetric inputs"],[773,"**Symptom:** `AttributeError` when calling an I/O or config function (e.g., `we.save`, `we.seterr`)"],[1001,"**Symptom:** `Connection refused` or `timeout`"],[454,"**Symptom:** `ImportError: numpy version mismatch`"],[1003,"**Symptom:** Port conflict"],[619,"**Symptom:** Unexpectedly high cost for multi-dimensional FFT"],[568,"**Symptom:** Unexpectedly high FLOP cost"],[775,"**Symptom:** Using `np.linalg.svd` instead of `we.linalg.svd`"],[726,"**Symptom:** Using `numpy.linalg.svd` instead of `we.linalg.svd`"],[617,"**Symptom:** Using `we.fft.fft` on real data when `we.fft.rfft` would suffice"],[942,"**Timeout:** 30 seconds per request"],[223,"**timing**"],[1373,"**TL;DR:** whest detects when an einsum expression has symmetry that allows computing fewer FLOPs. It does this by building a bipartite graph from the einsum subscripts, finding column permutations that preserve the graph structure, and using group theory to count how many unique terms exist. The savings can be dramatic -- a symmetric matrix multiplication can cost half as many FLOPs."],[471,"**Top rows:** `Used` is the total FLOP count spent so far across the current session, and `Remaining` shows the implicit global headroom"],[360,"**Total**"],[939,"**Transport:** ZMQ (REQ/REP pattern)"],[907,"**Unary pointwise ops** currently rebuild results from `symmetric_axes`, so\nthey preserve the same symmetric axes but not exact subgroup identity for\n`C_k`, `D_k`, or custom groups"],[1052,"**Unary** (exp, log, sqrt, ...)"],[36,"**Unified einsum cost model** — all einsum-like operations (einsum, dot, matmul, tensordot) now share a single cost model based on opt\\_einsum's contraction path optimizer"],[1088,"**Unique**"],[109,"**URL patterns:** `llms.txt` links to `.md` variants of each page (raw\nmarkdown for agents). Every page is also available as rendered HTML — just\ndrop the trailing `/index.md` from the URL:"],[524,"**Use cheaper operations.** A matrix-vector product costs `m*n` FLOPs, while a matrix-matrix product costs `m*n*k`. Avoid computing full matrix products when you only need a few rows or a single vector result."],[436,"**Use namespaces for phases.** Split your solution into named phases (e.g., `\"init\"`, `\"solve\"`, `\"refine\"`) so the budget summary shows exactly where FLOPs are spent."],[1384,"**V (free labels):** appear in the final output subscript or in operands\noutside the current subset (they \"cross the cut\")."],[1425,"**Validate pi:** require a bijective fingerprint match. In the JS\nexplorer, cross-V/W cycles are retained — a declared axis symmetry that\nlinks a V-axis with a W-axis (e.g., a symmetric matrix used as `A[i,j]`\nwith `i` free and `j` summed) produces a legitimate per-tuple symmetry\neven though it crosses the V/W boundary. The classification tree\n(singleton, young, directProduct, bruteForceOrbit) dispatches correctly\nbased on whether cross elements are present."],[1385,"**W (summed labels):** contracted entirely within the current subset."],[432,"**Wall / tracked / untracked time:** wall time is total elapsed time for the context, tracked time is time spent inside counted NumPy calls, and untracked time is everything else in the context (`wall_time - tracked_time`)"],[14,"**Wall-clock time limits.** `BudgetContext` now accepts `wall_time_limit_s` to\nset a wall-clock deadline. When exceeded, `TimeExhaustedError` is raised at the\nnext operation boundary with diagnostic info (operation name, elapsed time, limit).\nThe deadline is checked both before and after each numpy call (cooperative\nenforcement). The entry banner shows the time limit when set."],[1197,"**Wall-clock time normalization** -- measures `time(op) / time(add)` as\na relative proxy. Less precise than hardware counters but works on any\nplatform."],[439,"**Watch out for hidden costs.** Operations like `we.array()` and `we.concatenate()` are *not* free -- they charge `numel(output)` FLOPs, and `we.where()` charges `numel(condition)`. Check the cost of any operation you are unsure about."],[236,"**weight \\< 1.0** -- the operation is cheaper per analytical FLOP than `np.add` under the chosen calibration mode. This can happen because of efficient kernels, vectorization, library implementation details, or benchmarking noise; it should not be interpreted using the old “FMA counts as 2 FLOPs” convention, because whest uses FMA = 1 throughout the model"],[234,"**weight = 1.0** -- the operation has the same calibrated cost per analytical FLOP as `np.add` under the chosen measurement mode"],[235,"**weight > 1.0** -- the operation is more expensive per analytical FLOP than `np.add` under the chosen calibration mode (for example, transcendental functions such as `exp`)"],[82,"**whest is NOT NumPy.** It wraps a subset of NumPy with analytical FLOP\ncounting. Every arithmetic operation is charged against a budget. Code that\nworks with NumPy may fail or behave differently with whest:"],[1435,"**Why both?** Compression formulas (μ, α) must use $G_{\\text{pt}}$ — feeding them\n$G_{\\text{expr}}$ over-compresses, because dummy-rename orbits contain tuples whose\nsummand values differ. But the expression-level group is the \"natural\"\ncounting symmetry readers recognize: bilinear-trace has a Z₂ × Z₂ counting\nsymmetry even though only its Z₂ diagonal is per-tuple. Exposing both\ndistinguishes the *structural* story from the *compression-valid* story."],[40,"**Window functions** — `bartlett`, `hamming`, `hanning`, `blackman`, `kaiser` with per-function cost formulas"],[77,"**You will learn:**"],[193,"**You will learn:**"],[262,"**You will learn:**"],[404,"**You will learn:**"],[449,"**You will learn:**"],[463,"**You will learn:**"],[484,"**You will learn:**"],[540,"**You will learn:**"],[585,"**You will learn:**"],[636,"**You will learn:**"],[739,"**You will learn:**"],[799,"**You will learn:**"],[929,"**You will learn:**"],[976,"**You will learn:**"],[1029,"**You will learn:**"],[1215,"**You will learn:**"],[1298,"**You w