traction path table, `[W checkmark: ...]` indicates the inner reduction was\napplied, while `[W: ...]` indicates it was detected but not applied.\nInner symmetry can be toggled with `we.configure(use_inner_symmetry=False)`."],[1146,"The **output (V-side) reduction** is always applied when the step's\nintermediate has a non-trivial permutation group on its free indices —\nonly the unique output elements need to be computed."],[1452,"The **output (V-side) reduction** is always applied when the step's\nintermediate has a non-trivial permutation group on its free indices."],[1198,"The `benchmarks/` package in this repository automates both methods. See\nCalibrate Weights."],[982,"The `docker/` directory contains a ready-to-use setup:"],[1199,"The `flop_multiplier` parameter in `BudgetContext` scales all costs:"],[412,"The `namespace` parameter sets the root namespace prefix for that budget context. Nested `we.namespace(...)` scopes extend it with dotted segments, but they do not create child budgets or split the FLOP limit into separate pools."],[1152,"The analytical formulas above treat all operations within a category as\nequally expensive -- `exp`, `log`, `sin`, and `abs` all cost\n$\\text\\{numel\\}(\\text\\{output\\})$ FLOPs. In reality, `exp` decomposes into\na minimax polynomial approximation requiring approximately 14 FP\ninstructions per element, while `abs` is a single bit manipulation."],[733,"The basics"],[216,"The benchmark suite supports two measurement modes, chosen automatically:"],[1351,"The bipartite graph"],[1408,"The bipartite graph structure is fixed for the full einsum."],[427,"The block below shows `print(budget.summary(by_namespace=True))` for the `solver` context:"],[1263,"The categories determine how costs are calculated:"],[301,"The client package is independently installable, so its test suite can run via\nits own project file:"],[934,"The client-server model enforces this isolation:"],[993,"The containers share an IPC socket volume for communication."],[1381,"The core data structure is a bipartite graph over the einsum expression."],[1248,"The cost is always deterministic -- the same shapes produce the same FLOP count regardless of the data values or the hardware running the code."],[1042,"The cost is checked against the remaining budget"],[546,"The cost of an einsum is the sum of per-step costs along the optimal contraction path. Every einsum — even a simple two-operand one — goes through the opt\\_einsum path optimizer (a symmetry-aware fork of opt\\_einsum)."],[1356,"The detection algorithm"],[886,"The difference between full and non-full groups matters immediately:"],[1431,"The expression-level group factors cleanly (when restricted to V/W-\npreserving elements) as $V_{\\text{sub}} \\times S(W)$:"],[79,"The five rules for generating correct whest code"],[1448,"The fix has two parts:"],[1211,"The flow of a single call"],[206,"The generated `weights.json` is the source-of-truth artifact: it contains the\nper-operation weights plus metadata used by the generated docs and API data.\nThe packaged runtime file is a slim derivative used only for default loading."],[1406,"The incidence matrix M at this subset (rows = U-vertices, columns = V+W):"],[1439,"The incidence matrix M is the 4x4 identity. The only nontrivial sigma swaps\noperands 0 and 1, permuting rows (0 with 2, 1 with 3). Matching sigma(M) columns\nback to M columns gives:"],[1409,"The induced subgraph on a subset `S` is fully determined by which operands\nare in `S`."],[212,"The JSON file must have a `\"weights\"` key mapping operation names to floats:"],[1193,"The JSON file must have a `\"weights\"` key mapping operation names to floats:"],[1407,"The key invariant is the **pure-in-subset property**: the symmetry of an\nintermediate tensor depends only on the set of original operands it was formed\nfrom, not on the order in which they were contracted. This is because:"],[385,"The linalg suite has the most xfails (255) because whest's linalg wrappers don't support stacked/batched arrays, 0-size arrays, or some advanced kwargs that numpy's linalg tests exercise extensively."],[1376,"The naive approach is to rerun a detection procedure at every step for every\ncandidate subset. This is too expensive for large contractions. We want:"],[365,"The numpy\\_compat tests are excluded from the default `pytest` run (via `pyproject.toml` `addopts`) to prevent the monkeypatch from contaminating the main test suite. They run as a separate step in CI."],[1212,"The operation registry"],[1138,"The oracle builds a bipartite graph once per `contract_path` call and\nevaluates symmetry lazily per subset of operands encountered during path\nsearch. Both sources are merged via the same group-merging machinery, so a\ntensor that is both `SymmetricTensor` and also repeated in the subscript\nbenefits from both contributions simultaneously."],[1466,"The oracle evaluates each subset at most once. For a contract with `N` operands\nand groups of sizes `k_1, k_2, ...`:"],[614,"The output of `rfft` has shape `(n//2 + 1,)` instead of `(n,)`, since the negative frequencies are redundant for real inputs."],[560,"The printed table gives you the contraction order, naive-vs-optimized FLOP counts, largest intermediate, grouped index sizes, and one row per pairwise contraction step. Each step shows the chosen contract tuple, dense baseline, savings, BLAS tag, and any symmetry that survived into the intermediate."],[1350,"The problem"],[843,"The propagation examples below assume `import whest as we`; generated tensors\nabove use `we.random.symmetric(...)` and the explicit transform helper is\n`we.symmetrize(...)`."],[906,"The propagation rules are easier to predict if you keep three ideas in mind:"],[1259,"The registry (`whest/_registry.py`) is a mapping of every NumPy callable to its classification and cost behavior. Each entry specifies:"],[817,"the repeated `x` operand lets whest detect symmetric output and reduce the cost"],[296,"The root env