mmetry Explorer — choose a preset example or define your own einsum expression."],[399,"Wall-time limits"],[795,"Warnings, conservative behavior, and re-tagging"],[390,"We considered alternatives:"],[327,"We run 7 NumPy test modules covering core math, ufuncs, numerics, linear algebra, FFT, polynomials, and random:"],[312,"We solve this by **freezing numpy before patching**: the conftest creates a snapshot of the numpy module (and its submodules like `numpy.linalg`, `numpy.fft`), then rebinds every whest module's `_np` reference to the frozen copy. Now whest's internal calls go to the original numpy functions, while the test suite sees whest's versions."],[531,"we.dot and we.matmul"],[643,"Weight"],[680,"Weight"],[696,"Weight"],[1156,"Weight"],[1189,"Weights are applied centrally in `BudgetContext.deduct()`. Every counted\noperation passes its `op_name` to `deduct()`, which looks up the weight\nand multiplies it into the cost:"],[214,"Weights are applied centrally in `BudgetContext.deduct()`. Every counted operation passes its `op_name` to `deduct()`, which looks up the weight and multiplies it into the cost:"],[1182,"Weights are measured using the overhead-subtracted correction-factor\nmethodology described in FLOP Weight Calibration Results.\nThe formula is:"],[237,"Weights are platform-specific -- different CPUs, BLAS libraries, and libm implementations produce different values. Always measure on the target platform. Symmetry reductions are independent of weights: symmetry reduces the element count while the weight scales the per-element cost."],[1195,"Weights can be determined in two ways:"],[215,"Weights compose with `flop_multiplier` and with symmetry reductions -- symmetry reduces the element count, the weight scales the per-element cost, and both apply independently."],[417,"What `wall_time_limit_s` does and does not do:"],[183,"What are weights?"],[735,"What changes"],[1300,"What cost formulas apply to each counted sub-category"],[254,"What gets patched"],[153,"What happens"],[880,"What happens here:"],[890,"What happens here:"],[219,"What it measures"],[194,"What per-operation weights are and why they matter"],[734,"What stays the same"],[482,"What to do next"],[445,"What you'll see"],[460,"What you'll see"],[1112,"When a tensor is a `SymmetricTensor`, costs are reduced based on the number of unique elements rather than total elements. For a symmetric $n \\times n$ matrix, there are $n(n+1)/2$ unique elements instead of $n^2$."],[141,"When in doubt, check `ops.json`, the relevant `/api-data/ops/<slug>.json`, or the API Reference."],[1342,"When inputs are `SymmetricTensor`, many operations automatically get reduced costs. See Exploit Symmetry."],[1375,"When operands are `SymmetricTensor`s, their per-operand symmetry is known\nupfront. But there is a second source of symmetry: when the same Python object\nappears at multiple operand positions, the output can be symmetric in index\nlabels contributed by those repeated operands -- even if the operands are dense."],[1287,"When per-operation weights are loaded, the analytical cost is multiplied by the operation's weight before deduction. This allows the cost model to reflect that `exp` is more expensive than `abs` in terms of actual hardware instructions, while keeping the base formulas simple and deterministic."],[299,"When running the local docs site and you want whest error messages to link to\nyour local copy instead of the hosted site, set:"],[553,"When symmetric tensors are involved, each step's cost is further reduced by the ratio of unique output elements to total output elements. See Symmetry Savings for the full practical guide."],[1150,"When symmetric tensors are present, the optimizer is symmetry-aware: it\nuses symmetric costs to decide which pair to contract at each step, so the\nreturned path may differ from the dense-optimal path. Symmetry propagates\nthrough intermediates — if an early contraction produces a symmetric\nintermediate, subsequent steps benefit from the reduced element count, and\nthe optimizer factors this into its ordering decisions."],[1143,"When symmetry is present, whest reduces each step's cost based on\nthe structure of the contraction."],[1455,"When the generated group equals S\\_k (the full symmetric group, checked via\n`order == k!`), the existing stars-and-bars formula `C(n+k-1, k)` applies.\nWhen the group is a proper subgroup (e.g., C\\_3 from `einsum('ij,jk,ki->', A, A, A)`),\nBurnside's lemma gives the exact unique element count."],[498,"When the time limit is exceeded, whest raises `TimeExhaustedError` at the next\noperation boundary. The summary exposes three timing views:"],[402,"When things go wrong"],[804,"When to re-tag results with `we.as_symmetric()` after conservative propagation"],[802,"When to use `we.random.symmetric()` (sample + project) versus `we.symmetrize()`\n(project existing data)"],[179,"When to use this page"],[924,"When to use which"],[1405,"When we restrict to subset `{A, B}`, labels `i` and `j` cross the cut (they also\nappear in T, outside the subset), so they move from W to V:"],[1229,"When you call a counted operation, whest computes its FLOP cost analytically from the tensor shapes *before* the operation executes. The cost depends on the operation category:"],[503,"When you hit a `BudgetExhaustedError`, the budget's operation log gives per-call detail:"],[832,"When you want example tensors for arbitrary groups, prefer `we.random.symmetric`.\nIt is a handy helper that samples from a distribution and applies the Reynolds\noperator.\nUse `we.symmetrize` when you already have concrete data to symmetrize, and\n`we.as_symmetric` when you already have concrete data to validate and tag."],[613,"When your input is real-valued (which is common in signal processing), prefer `rfft` over `fft` — it costs half as much:"],[228,"where `alpha_raw(op)` depends on the active measurement mode:"],[1184,"where $\\alpha_\\{\\text\\{raw\\}\\}$ is the median ratio of hardware-observed FP\ninstructions to analytical FLOPs (FMA = 1 op), measured via\n`fp_arith_inst_retired` performance counters. The ufunc dispatch overhead\n(measured from `np.abs`, which generates zero FP arithmetic) is subtracted\nper category to remove numpy implementation noise from the weight."],[1024,"Where weights come from"],[753,"whest"],[1039,"whest computes FLOP costs **analytically from tensor shapes**, not by measuring execution time."],[1041,"whest computes the cost from the shapes: 256 × 256 = 65,536 FLOPs"],[374,"whest doesn't support this dtype"],[1220,"whest exposes a NumPy-compatible API. When you write `import whest as we` and call `we.einsum(...)`, you get a function that behaves like `np.einsum(...)` but with FLOP counting layered on top."],[319,"whest functions are plain callables, not ufuncs -- they lack `.reduce`, `.accumulate`, `.outer`, `.nargs`. Tests check these attributes at collection time."],[311,"whest functions internally call numpy (e.g., `we.dot` calls `_np.dot`). Since `_np` IS the numpy module, patching `numpy.dot = we.dot` would cause infinite recursion: `we.dot` → `_np.dot` → `numpy.dot` → `we.dot` → ..."],[902,"Whest propagates symmetry metadata conservatively. When the operation does not\nguarantee that the declared symmetry survives, the result falls back to a plain\n`ndarray`."],[489,"whest provides cost query functions that compute FLOP costs from shapes without executing anything or touching the budget. Use these to plan before committing FLOPs:"],[209,"whest ships with packaged official weights and loads them automatically on a\nnormal import."],[199,"whest's analytical cost formulas treat all operations within a category equally -- `exp`, `log`, `sin`, and `abs` all cost `numel(output)` FLOPs for a pointwise unary operation. In reality, `exp` decomposes into a minimax polynomial approximation requiring approximately 14 floating-point instructions per element, while `abs` is a single bit manipulation."],[309,"whest's goal is to be a drop-in replacement for NumPy: `import whest as np` should work for all supported functions. To verify this, we run NumPy's own test suite against whest."],[244,"Which environment to use"],[741,"Which NumPy behaviors stay the same and which change"],[1301,"Which operations are blocked and why"],[920,"Why client-server?"],[1009,"Why FLOPs instead of wall-clock time"],[809,"Why it drops"],[259,"Why monkeypatching (not subclassing)"],[316,"Why skipped"],[780,"Why symmetry matters"],[930,"Why whest uses a client-server model for competition evaluation"],[580,"Windowed FFT pattern"],[970,"With Docker Compose"],[971,"Without Docker"],[1352,"Worked example"],[1362,"Worked examples"],[759,"Works anywhere too"],[151,"Wrap known-symmetric matrices with `we.as_symmetric(data, symmetric_axes=(0, 1))`\nfor automatic savings in downstream ops"],[766,"Wrap with `we.as_symmetric()` for cost savings"],[331,"xfailed"],[1040,"You call a counted operation (e.g., `we.einsum('ij,j->i', W, x)`)"],[564,"You can also specify a completely custom path. Each tuple names the positions (in the current operand list) to contract; the result is appended to the end:"],[467,"You do not need to set up a budget context to start counting FLOPs. whest activates a global default context the first time any counted operation runs. The default budget is 1e15 FLOPs (configurable via the `WHEST_DEFAULT_BUDGET` environment variable)."],[1280,"Zero FLOP cost"],[1072,"zeros, reshape, etc."],[275,"ZMQ server that executes the real library"]],"type":"string"},"page_id":{"docs":{"1":115,"2":116,"3":117,"4":118,"5":119,"6":120,"7":121,"8":122,"9":123,"10":124,"11":125,"12":126,"13":127,"14":128,"15":129,"16":130,"17":131,"18":132,"19":133,"20":134,"21":135,"22":136,"23":137,"24":138,"25":139,"26":140,"27":141,"28":142,"29":143,"30":144,"31":145,"32":146,"33":147,"34":148,"35":149,"36":150,"37":151,"38":152,"39":153,"40":154,"41":155,"42":156,"43":157,"44":158,"45":159,"46":160,"47":161,"48":162,"49":163,"50":164,"51":165